      <p class="lead">Shan Tuyet ancient tea is one of Vietnam's most distinctive agricultural products. Grown wild on 200+ year-old tea trees in the misty highlands of Ha Giang province, these hand-picked leaves yield a tea of remarkable smoothness and depth — a product that Greenie Vietnam now brings to global premium tea retailers and private label brands.</p>

      <h2>The Old Growth</h2>
      <p>These are not plantation rows of waist-high shrubs. Shan Tuyet trees stand 4 to 12 meters tall — true forest sentinels with trunks thick as ancient oaks, their canopies interweaving with wild orchids, epiphytic ferns, and the velvet moss unique to Ha Giang's limestone karst.</p>

      <blockquote>
        <p><strong>Dendrological Heritage:</strong> Core samples from the oldest specimens in Hoang Su Phi district confirm a minimum age of 270 years. These trees were already mature when the Tay Son Rebellion reshaped Vietnam in the 18th century.</p>
      </blockquote>

      <p>The H'Mông and Dao ethnic communities who tend these trees do not farm them in any conventional sense. They are guardians of a wild ecosystem, harvesting only the "one bud, two leaves" standard — a protocol that respects the tree's physiological limits and ensures continued vitality.</p>

      <p>At 1,200 to 1,800 meters above sea level, the trees endure winters where temperatures approach freezing on the highest ridges, only to be enveloped by thick montane clouds for up to 240 days per year. This perpetual altitude stress slows leaf metabolism dramatically, concentrating amino acids, catechins, and volatile aromatic compounds to levels rarely seen in cultivated teas.</p>

      <blockquote>
        <p>In every cup of Shan Tuyet, you taste 270 years of rain, limestone, and cloud.</p>
        <footer>— Greenie Vietnam Tea Collection</footer>
      </blockquote>

      <h2>The Sensory Architecture</h2>
      <p>Shan Tuyet defies the bitterness often associated with large-leaf teas.</p>

      <figure>
        <img src="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1556679343-c7306c1976bc?auto=format&fit=crop&q=80&w=800" alt="H'Mông artisan hand-picking ancient Shan Tuyet tea leaves in Ha Giang cloud forest" loading="lazy" />
        <figcaption>A H'Mông guardian harvests "one bud, two leaves" at 1,800m — a protocol unchanged for centuries.</figcaption>
      </figure>

      <p>What makes Shan Tuyet extraordinary is its absence of astringency. While most large-leaf teas carry a pronounced bitterness, Shan Tuyet's high-altitude amino acid concentration — particularly L-theanine — creates a natural sweetness that coats the palate. This is the direct result of stress metabolism: at 1,200 to 1,800 meters, cold nights and mist-shrouded days force the trees to produce protective compounds that translate into extraordinary cup complexity.</p>

      <p>The leaves themselves tell the story. Each is thick and leathery — an adaptation to altitude — with a silvery down on the underside that gives the tea its name: "Shan Tuyet" means "snow on the mountain," referring both to the frost-touched peaks where the trees grow and the white-haired appearance of the young buds.</p>

      <h3>Tasting Notes</h3>

      <p><strong>Dry Leaf Aroma:</strong> Wood-fired honey, aged cedar, and the faintest trace of wild jasmine from epiphytic companions in the forest canopy.</p>
      <p><strong>Liquor Color:</strong> Pale champagne gold with remarkable clarity — a visual signature of the high-altitude amino acid concentration.</p>
      <p><strong>First Infusion:</strong> A silken entry of chestnut honey and steamed rice cake, followed by a mid-palate that opens like wild orchid nectar — sweet but never cloying.</p>
      <p><strong>Finish:</strong> The "shan yun" (mountain rhyme) — a lingering mineral coolness reminiscent of limestone spring water, persisting for 15 minutes after the cup is empty.</p>

      <h2>The Harvest Calendar</h2>
      <p>The finest Shan Tuyet is harvested in three distinct windows:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Spring Harvest (March-April)</strong> — The crown jewel. Post-winter dormancy concentrates maximum sweetness and floral complexity. Our premium export grade.</li>
        <li><strong>Summer Harvest (June-July)</strong> — Bolder, more vegetal. Preferred by buyers seeking robust character for blending or daily consumption lines.</li>
        <li><strong>Autumn Harvest (September-October)</strong> — Mellow and smooth, with pronounced honey notes. Limited quantity, often reserved by advance contract.</li>
      </ul>

